  "issue_title": "[Bug]: Status requests over NATS never receive a reply and time out",
  "issue_body": "### Description\n\nThe `EventBus` supports request and reply. A handler registered with `is_request_handler=True` receives the message object and answers through `msg.respond()`, while the caller uses `EventBus.request()`. Cache, external-api, and overrides already use this correctly.\n\nFive services instead answer a status request by publishing to a separate subject, or do not answer at all:\n\n- kernel subscribes to `kernel.status` as a plain subscription, then publishes to `kernel.status.response`.\n- meta-programmer subscribes to `metaprogrammer.status`, then publishes to `metaprogrammer.status.response`.\n- safety-supervisor subscribes to `safety.status`, then publishes to `safety.status.response`.\n- coordinator subscribes to `coordinator.status`, then publishes to `coordinator.status.result`.\n- planner subscribes to `planner.status`, then only logs the status and never replies.\n\nNothing subscribes to those response subjects. A caller that does `event_bus.request(\"<service>.status\", ...)` waits on the reply inbox and times out, because the handler answered on a different subject or did not answer at all. Status reporting is read only and advisory, so this is a correctness and consistency gap rather than a safety regression, but every status query to these five services fails today.\n\n### Steps to Reproduce\n\n1. Start an affected service, for example `python run.py --only kernel`.\n2. From any NATS client, send a request to its status subject, for example `nats req kernel.status '{}'`, or in code `await event_bus.request(\"kernel.status\", {}, timeout=2.0)`.\n3. Watch the request inbox: no reply ever arrives.\n4. The request times out.\n\n### Expected Behavior\n\nThe status handler replies on the request inbox via `msg.respond()`, the same way cache, external-api, and overrides do, so `event_bus.request(...)` returns the status payload.\n\n### Actual Behavior\n\n```shell\n$ nats req kernel.status '{}'\n12:00:00 Sending request on \"kernel.status\"\nnats: error: nats: timeout\n\n# In code the request raises after the timeout, because the handler published the\n# status to kernel.status.response (which has no subscribers) instead of replying:\n#   asyncio.TimeoutError\n```\n\n### Environment\n\n- OS: Ubuntu 24.04 (Linux)\n- Python: 3.11 and 3.12\n- Run mode: `python run.py` (pure Python); also reproduces under Docker Compose\n- Hardware: not relevant\n- Note: this is a logic defect in the request handling, independent of platform\n  and hardware.\n\n### Pre-submission checks\n\n- [x] I searched existing issues and this is not a duplicate.\n- [x] I am running the latest `main` (or I have stated my version/commit).",
